  "text": "The Kubernetes API object write chain from API server handler to etcd storage follows this flow:\n\n## 1. REST Handler Layer\nThe Pod REST storage is initialized in `pkg/registry/core/pod/storage/storage.go` via the `NewStorage` function (line 72), which creates a `REST` struct that embeds `*genericregistry.Store`. This handler receives the HTTP request for Pod creation.\n\n## 2. Generic Registry Store\nThe core storage logic resides in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/registry/generic/registry/store.go`. The `Store.Create` method (line 446) is the entry point for all create operations. It:\n- Calls `e.Storage.Create()` at line 526, where `e.Storage` is of type `DryRunnableStorage`\n- The storage is configured through `RESTOptions` which contains a `StorageConfig` object\n\n## 3. Dry-Run Storage Wrapper\nIn `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/registry/generic/registry/dryrun.go`, the `DryRunnableStorage` struct (line 30) wraps the actual storage backend. Its `Create` method (line 39) delegates to `s.Storage.Create()` for non-dry-run requests, where `s.Storage` is of type `storage.Interface`.\n\n## 4. etcd3 Store Implementation\nThe actual etcd3 storage is implemented in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/store.go`. The `store.Create` method (line 241) performs the following:\n- Line 260: Encodes the object using `runtime.Encode(s.codec, obj)` which uses the Codec\n- Line 275: Transforms the encoded data using `s.transformer.TransformToStorage()` for encryption/compression\n- Line 283: Calls `s.client.Kubernetes.OptimisticPut()` to write to etcd\n\n## 5. Codec and Serialization\nThe codec comes from `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/storagebackend/config.go` where it's defined as `Codec runtime.Codec` (line 67). This is created by `serializer.NewCodecFactory()` from `staging/src/k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/runtime/serializer/codec_factory.go`.\n\nThe actual JSON serialization is implemented in `staging/src/k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/runtime/serializer/json/json.go` through the `Serializer` struct (line 99) which handles encoding Kubernetes objects to JSON format using Go's standard `encoding/json` package.\n\n## 6. Value Transformation\nBefore writing to etcd, the serialized data is transformed using the `Transformer` interface from `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/value/transformer.go` (line 59). This transformer can apply encryption (AES-GCM), compression, or other transformations to the data.\n\n## 7. Decoder\nAfter the etcd write completes, the response is decoded using `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/decoder.go` with the default decoder created by `NewDefaultDecoder()` (line 135).\n\n## 8. etcd Client\nThe actual etcd client that performs the Put operation is from `go.etcd.io/etcd/client/v3/kubernetes`, where the `OptimisticPut` method wraps transaction logic around the etcd v3 client's KV operations to ensure atomicity.\n\nThe complete write chain ensures that Kubernetes objects are properly serialized, validated, transformed for storage, and written atomically to etcd with proper versioning and precondition handling."
